Methods, 2016, 8, 2653 Received 29th September 2015 Accepted 24th February 2016 DNA is known as a potential therapeutic target because any damage on its chain may aﬀect DNA replication leading to cell death. Many anticancer and antibiotics agents have their biolog- ical activity related to DNA interactions. These compounds may display either novel modes of interaction with DNA or interesting functions.1,2 There are many ways in which a small molecule can interact with DNA aﬀecting its structure and function.3 For instance, the planar ring systems of anthracyclines (known as anticancer compounds) intercalate between DNA base pairs and their sugar(s) interact(s) with a minor groove.4,5 Another example is ethidium bromide, an organic dye much used in molecular biology, which also intercalates between DNA base pairs.6 Microbial sources are well known as an important provider of a large diversity of pharmacotherapeutic compounds, and they aMass Spectrometry and Natural Products Laboratory – Departamento de Qu´ımica da Faculdade de Filosoa, Ciˆencias e Letras de Ribeir˜ao Preto, Universidade de S˜ao Paulo, CEP: 14040-900, Ribeir˜ao Preto, SP, Brazil. DNA is known as a potential therapeutic target for the development of anticancer and antibiotic agents because any damage on its structure may lead to cell death. Discovery of ligand molecules through interactions with DNA is a key step in the development of new therapies. Here, a methodology was proposed to detect DNA-binders in a screening process with crude extracts produced by actinomycetes. This assay consists of a DNA–EB (ethidium bromide) complex added previously, into a simple agarose gel, where EB may be replaced by other metabolites, present in the sample added before over the gel. The free dye is washed and, consequently, the ﬂuorescence intensity decreases. The assay results were recorded by photographs and the ﬂuorescence intensity was transposed in pixel values using Image J software, allowing statistical analyses. The developed assay can also be applied directly onto TLC plates. Sixteen crude extracts produced by actinomycetes were screened using the developed assay, in which four crude extracts showed a signiﬁcant ﬂuorescence decrease. Dereplication studies with mass spectra data allowed the identiﬁcation of anthracyclines such as Ditrisarubicin F and G in one of the selected extracts. The methodology developed here is a promising approach for drug discovery because it may lead to the detection of DNA-binding compounds in a simple, low cost way and without isolation and/or puriﬁcation processes.

have extensively been explored for drug discovery research.7 However, the chemical diversity of secondary metabolites chal- lenges the processes of bioactive compound isolation and puri- cation. Thus, screening strategies may be more attractive to apply in natural products to guide and facilitate the identication of novel biological activity compounds. A variety of physico- chemical and biochemical techniques have been applied to screen and study DNA-binding complexes, such as Raman spec- troscopy,8 agarose gel electrophoresis,9 resonance light scattering (RLS), ultraviolet (UV) spectroscopy, 1H NMR spectroscopy10 and others. On-line combination of chromatographic, mass spec- trometry and uorescence techniques has also been employed eﬃciently, to obtain HPLC ngerprint, UV spectra, MSn fragments and DNA-binding proles of crude extracts, as an approach to save time.11,12 Nevertheless, these methodologies are expensive to be used for a large amount of sample (e.g. screening processes), needing sophisticated equipment and laboratories. In this work, two simple, low cost and rapid approaches were used in an assay to screen in vitro compounds with interactions to DNA. The methodology presented here was very suitable to detect DNA ligand compounds present in the crude extract produced by actinomycete CS039. Dereplication of the active crude extract employing tandem mass spectrometry allowed the identication of Ditrisarubicin F and G, both belonging to the anthracycline class. Anal. Agarose was bought from Agargen. DNA from herring sperm, ethidium bromide, Safranin T, doxorubicin (Dox), daunoru- bicin (Dnr), colchicine (Colch), combretastatin A-4 (CA-4), vinblastine (Vinblast), and camptothecin (CPT) were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich. Gel-Red nucleic acid stain was obtained from Biotium. All the above compounds were used without further purication. Dox and Dnr stock solutions were prepared (cid:1)1 (w/v). DNA in HPLC grade methanol (MeOH) at 200 mg mL (cid:1)1 stock solution was prepared in ultra-pure water at 1 mg mL (w/v), and ethidium bromide (EB) and Safranin T (SfT) stock solutions were prepared in HPLC grade MeOH at 20 mM. A DNA : EB mixture was prepared by adding 50% of each, leading (cid:1)1 and EB 10 mM. The to a nal concentration of DNA 0.5 mg mL DNA concentration was determined according to absorbance at 260 nm aer establishing the absorbance ratio, A260/A280, to be in the range of 1.80–1.90. This indicated that the DNA was free from protein. Microorganisms Actinomycetes were kindly provided by Coleç˜ao de Micro- rganismos de Importˆancia Agr´ıcola e Ambiental (CCMA, EMBRAPA, Brazil). The strains were maintained as mycelia fragments in glycerol (20%, v/v) at (cid:1)20 (cid:3)C, and reactivated on plates of GYEA (glucose-yeast extract agar)13 at room temperature.

Crude extracts Actinomycetes were cultivated in 125 mL Erlenmeyer asks containing 25 mL PD (potato-dextrose) medium at 30 (cid:3)C under shaking conditions (150 rpm) for 10 days. Crude extracts were obtained by simple liquid culture ltration followed by liquid– liquid extraction with ethyl acetate. The organic phase was dried and the crude extracts obtained were diluted with MeOH at (cid:1)1, and the solution was a nal concentration of 10.0 mg mL stored at 4 (cid:3)C. Agarose 1.0% was dissolved in ultra-pure water, heated in a microwave oven, and poured into an 8 (cid:4) 12 cm plastic plate. Aer solidication, 2 mL DNA : EB mixture was pipetted on the gel surface in diﬀerent spots. Samples (2 mL) were pipetted exactly in the same spot where the DNA–EB mixture was previ- ously pipetted. G-DNA–EB – gel-DNA–ethidium bromide Agarose 1.0% was dissolved in ultra-pure water and heated in a microwave oven, and before solidication, diﬀerent percentages of the DNA : EB mixture were added into the solution (5–25%). Samples were pipetted in diﬀerent spots on the gel surface. All experiments were developed in triplicate. Aer pipetting samples on the gels, both gel types (SAG and G-DNA–EB) were le for 30 minutes for sample permeation, and then submerged in ultra-pure water and kept under shaking conditions (80 rpm) for 20 minutes. The gels were photographed on a uorescent transilluminator [302 nm wavelength (l)]. The images were processed using Image J soware14 and pixel values were considered for each point for statistical analyses. The method specicity was evaluated using Safranin T (SnT) (cid:1)1, before and Gel-Red (GR), at 20 mM, mixture to DNA 1 mg mL being pipetted on the SAG surface, and aer 30 minutes Dox was pipetted. The solvent eﬀect was also evaluated in the developed assay and the following solvents were tested: DMSO (dimethyl-sulf- oxide), MeOH (methanol), EtOH (ethanol), DMF (N,N-dimethyl- formamide), ACN (acetonitrile), acetone, ethyl acetate, chloro- form and hexane. To evaluate the sensitivity of the developed assay, two compounds Dox and Dnr, known as DNA-binders, were used at 200, 100, 50, 10, 1.0 and 0.1 mg mL The method was evaluated using anticancer standards with diﬀerent modes of action: doxorubicin, daunorubicin, colchi- cine, combretastatin A-4, vinblastine and camptothecin. All of (cid:1)1. Vinblastine was dissolved in them were tested at 200 mg mL DMSO and the other standards in MeOH. Crude extracts obtained from actinomycetes were subjected to the DNA-binding developed assay, applying 2 mL of each only on the SAG gel.

Mass spectrometry analyses Mass spectrometry analyses (full scan and CID – Collision Induced Dissociation) were carried out by employing an Acquity™ UHPLC system (Waters®) consisting of a quaternary pump and an automatic injector coupled to a Xevo TQ-S mass spectrometer with a Z-spray orthogonal ionization source ESI (electrospray) (Waters®). CID experiments were performed in positive ionization mode (ESI+), and the MS parameters are as follows: 3.2 kV capillary voltage, 40 V skimmer voltage, 300 (cid:3)C (cid:1)1 gas ow, 5.0 bar desolvation chamber temperature, 600 L h nebulizer gas, and 30 eV collision energy. For data acquisition and processing, Masslynx 4.1 soware (Waters Corp., Milford, MA, USA) was used. Statistical analyses The data obtained were analyzed in GraphPad Prism 5.0 so- ware using ANOVA and the Tukey test. 5.0% signicance (p < 0.05 value) was considered. DNA oﬀers a number of potential binding sites and modes of noncovalent interactions for small molecules. Many organic dyes have already been proven to be sensitive probes to DNA, This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2016 (cid:1)1 dissolved in MeOH. such as ethidium bromide (EB),15,16 acridine orange (AO),17 diphenylamine blue18 and neutral red,19 among others. These organic dyes have a planar aromatic system that can be inserted between two adjacent base pairs in a helix and incorporate a positive charge.

A simple, fast and low cost DNA-binding assay was devel- oped, optimized and used to screen crude extracts produced by Brazilian actinomycetes. The DNA-binding assay was developed to reduce the number of samples and focused on the search for DNA binders in crude extracts. The focus of this work was the development of a simple assay to detect DNA binders as promising anticancer agents in complex samples such as microbial crude extracts. The DNA-binding assay developed is a simple method that could be applied in many laboratories, in other words, this without necessary high technologies; approach is appropriate to detect DNA-binders. For identica- tion, other techniques such as liquid chromatography, mass spectrometry, nuclear magnetic resonance and others are necessary, although the developed method helps in guiding the identication and reduces the number of samples to be analyzed by advanced techniques. The DNA-binding assay uses agarose gel as a support for DNA in a way that the compounds could be in contact with the DNA and those that are not bound could be released by washing. The organic dyes bound to DNA could be substituted by another binder; this replacement occurs due to the presence of secondary metabolites in the crude extracts with higher aﬃnity to DNA. The organic dye released could be eliminated by washing, and the positive results show that the uorescent spot intensity was gradually decreased according to organic dye release.

In this work, two diﬀerent methods with the same principle, SAG and G-DNA–EB, were developed. At beginning, the (1) SAG methodology was developed and optimized to use low amounts of sample. Aer that, the SAG gel was changed, developing the (2) G-DNA–EB, making it possible to be applied directly onto TLC plates, to guide the isolation of the compounds detected as DNA binders. To developed the DNA-binding assay, we used a well know DNA binder, doxorubicin, a low cost DNA and agarose gel as a simple support for them. For these, various conditions including the agarose gel concentration, the DNA and EB concentration on gel, EB displacement time and the Dox concentration were investigated (data not shown). Finally, SAG was applied to screen sixteen crude extracts leading to the detection of four samples containing promising anticancer compounds. Mass spectrometry allowed the identication of Ditrisarubicin D and G, in one of the crude extracts. These compounds belong to a class of anthracyclines, known as DNA- binding. (a) DNA-binding assay specicity. The eﬀect of diﬀerent organic dyes rather than ethidium bromide (EB), such as Gel- Red (GR) and Safranin T (SfT), which are compounds that are less dangerous and have similar performances, on uorescent spot intensity was evaluated.20 Solutions were prepared by This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2016

adding 50% of each (DNA + one organic dye), leading to a nal (cid:1)1 and organic dye 10 mM. A concentration of DNA 0.5 mg mL solution was prepared for each organic dye separated. 2 mL of the solution DNA + organic dye was pipetted onto the gel surface and held until the drop was completely absorbed by the gel, (cid:1)1 was approximately 15 minutes (Fig. 1A). 2 mL Dox 200 mg mL added exactly on the same spot pipetted previously and held until the drop was completely absorbed by the gel and inter- acted with DNA, approximately 30 minutes. More time is necessary for organic dyes, and other compounds to interact with DNA; however, it was observed that more than 40 minutes disperse the DNA and the spot uorescence cannot be measured any longer. The same eﬀect was observed for washing for more than 20 minutes. Fig. 1B shows the uorescence intensity aer washing for 20 min. Ethidium bromide is suitable as a uorescent marker of nucleic acids because it binds to DNA, and for this reason it is the most commonly used organic dye in molecular biology laboratories. Ethidium bromide (DNA + EB + Dox) proved to be the best organic dye to be used in this method (Fig. 1B), pre- senting a uorescence intensity decrease of 56% relative to the control (DNA + EB). Gel-Red showed a uorescence intensity decrease of 41% relative to the control, which shows that the DNA-binding assay can be used with other safer markers than ethidium bromide, such as Gel-Red. In contrast, no uores- cence was observed with Safranin T and this could be due to the wavelength (302 nm) used by the transilluminator. The ideal wavelength absorbance of Safranin T is 520 nm.

(b) Solvent eﬀect. Crude extracts from natural products, or even pure compounds are usually dissolved in a wide variety of organic solvents, such as MeOH, acetonitrile, DMSO and others. Therefore, the organic solvent eﬀect was also investigated as it could cause interference in the uorescent spot intensity (Table S1†). N,N-Dimethyl-formamide (DMF) caused a little decrease in the uorescence intensity compared with the other solvents, but it was not a signicant decrease. This result means that the organic solvents tested can be used in this DNA-binding assay without inuencing the uorescent spot intensity. (c) DNA-binding assay sensitivity. (d) DNA-binding assay selectivity. The method selectivity was evaluated using known anticancer standards with diﬀerent modes of action: DNA-binders (doxorubicin and daunorubicin), tubulin-binders (colchicine, combretastatin-A4 and vinblas- tine)21 and topoisomerase-binder (camptothecin).22 As expected, only DNA-binders, Dox and Dnr, exhibited a statistically signicant decrease in uorescence intensity, (cid:5)59% and (cid:5)57%, respectively. None of the other standards used with diﬀerent modes of action showed signicant changes in uorescence intensity (Fig. 2); in other words, these compounds did not interact with DNA in the DNA-binding assay, as expected, once their mode of action is binding to other targets. This result demonstrates that the developed method can be used in DNA- binder detection. Camptothecin (CPT), a uorescent compound (excitation: l m´ax 450 nm),23 increased the uorescence intensity; nevertheless, this increase was not statistically signicant. It is important to note that compounds which are able to replace EB in DNA, but also have the same uorescence emission range, can lead to a false negative result. Thus, in this kind of study, it is also necessary to evaluate the crude extract uorescence to exclude any false-negative results. (e) Screening of crude extracts by the SAG methodology. Once the experimental conditions for the SAG methodology were optimized, it was applied in a screening process with sixteen crude extracts produced by actinomycetes (Table 2). Lower uorescence intensity was observed for crude extracts CS039 ((cid:5)76%), SB074 ((cid:5)74%), SB003R ((cid:5)84%) and SB019 ((cid:5)94%), and Dox ((cid:5)49%) when they were compared with control DNA + EB (100%). A methodology established by Song et al.26 allows the detection of DNA-binders on-line, combining techniques such as HPLC, DAD (Diode Array Detector) and high resolution mass spectrometry. Nevertheless, all these method- ologies require high technology equipment and a specialized workforce. Besides that, these kinds of analyses are expensive, which makes their application impracticable, in many labora- tories, in studies with large amounts of sample. Therefore, the methodology developed here is really good to be used in screening processes, since it can reduce the number of samples to be analyzed by these techniques.

In laboratories which work with natural products it is common to start projects with crude extracts. This kind of sample is complex and they are initially analyzed by Thin Layer Chro- matography (TLC) to obtain chemical and physical character- istics about the compounds present in the crude extracts. It would be impressive if there was a way to detect directly on TLC plates which compounds are able to bind to DNA, facilitating the isolation process. Thus, a second assay was also proposed employing the G-DNA–EB methodology, which could be applied directly onto TLC plates. Diﬀerent from the SAG methodology, where the mixture DNA : EB was pipetted on agarose gel to form a uorescent spot, in the G-DNA–EB methodology the gel was prepared by adding the DNA : EB mixture into the gel, before gelling, forming a uorescent gel. (a) G-DNA–EB preparation. Diﬀerent concentrations of the DNA : EB mixture [5, 10, 15 and 20% (v/v)] in the gel were evaluated. Data showed [Fig. S1(A)†] that the gel uorescence intensity increased proportionately with the increase in the DNA : EB concentration, as expected. In the same gels, 2 mL Dox 20 mM were pipetted, in duplicate [Fig. S1(B)†]. The positive results are observed by the decrease in uorescence in the spot where Dox solution was added. The G-DNA–EB with the DNA : EB mixture 5% (v/v) was chosen for the following exper- iments due to its high contrast.

(b) G-DNA–EB onto the TLC plate. To analyze if the DNA- binder (Dox) could migrate from the TLC plate to the G-DNA– EB, a TLC plate was used with Dox pipetted previously in diﬀerent concentrations. Then, the G-DNA–EB gel was put in contact with the TLC plate. The time to keep them in contact was also evaluated and 1 hour was chosen due to being the best time for Dox to migrate from the TLC plate and forming a dened dark spot in the uorescent gel (Fig. 3). Fig. 3B shows that the gel uorescence intensity decreases referring to the Dox spots on the TLC plate shown in Fig. 3A. This result means that Dox was able to migrate from the TLC plate to the G-DNA–EB gel. This experiment proves the impor- tance of this kind of gel development, allowing its use routinely in laboratories for rapid detection of DNA binders in complex mixtures like microbial crude extracts. The meth- odology developed in this work is simple, easy to apply, and mainly of low cost, making it extremely interesting in screening processes for a large number of natural product extracts. Anthracyclines identied in the crude extract produced by actinomycete CS039 The crude extract produced by actinomycete CS039 was active in the DNA-binding assay developed in this work; for this reason, this extract was subjected to dereplication studies employing the data obtained from full scan MS (Fig. S2†); CID experiments and further physical characteristics and biological sources were also used to search in the Dictionary of Natural Products. The search results suggest that the anthracycline class was found. In the ESI+ full scan spectrum, interesting ion groups can be observed in the m/z 570 to 610 range (ions m/z 577, 585, 593, 601 and 609). The m/z diﬀerence of 8 units between them suggests that they are double-charged [M + 2H]2+. Thus, the ions with lower intensity m/z 1153, 1169, 1185, 1201 and 1217 refer to the same compounds with only one charge [M + H]+.

To obtain additional structural information, the ions with m/z 1169 and 1185 were fragmented by CID (Fig. S2,† and 4). Anal. Ditrisarubicins are anthracyclines with anticancer activity produced by Streptomyces cyaneus MG344-hF4.27 This group of anthracyclines with two trisaccharide chain have been widely studied as promising anticancer agents due their lower toxicity in tumor cells.24,28 This journal is © The Royal Society of Chemistry 2016 In summary, two new methodologies were successfully devel- oped for DNA-binding studies for simple and fast compound monitoring with potential to interact with DNA, employing agarose gel. The sensitivity was evaluated and doxorubicin was (cid:1)1 concentration. This detected in both gels even at a 10 mg mL assay was optimized and the obtained results showed that this new assay can be used to screen a great amount of extracts in a cheap and eﬃcient way, besides its use in diﬀerent modes of action studies. Natural product sources are well known as an important provider of a large diversity of pharmacotherapeutic compounds; in other words, they have extensively been explored for drug discovery research.7 However, the chemical diversity of secondary metabolites challenges the processes of bioactive compound isolation and purication. Thus, screening strate- gies may be more attractive to apply in natural products to guide and facilitate the identication of novel biological activity compounds. Natural product screening processes normally begin with a great amount of samples, and for this reason, methodologies with low cost and a fast response are really desired. Since the developed assay is based on uorescence intensity changes, false-negative results may be obtained by DNA-binding compounds with uorescence. This methodology allowed detecting compounds known as DNA-binders in a crude extract actinomycetes. The dereplication process produced by employing tandem mass spectrometry allowed the identica- tion of the anthracyclines, Ditrisarubicin F and G, in crude extracts from actinomycete CS039.
